A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
But the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that election fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on participation rates.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
With this in mind, a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 making it more difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states join.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of voting rights were introduced in 41 states in 2011 alone.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the time for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day and deprive citizens with a judicial record of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities quickly extended the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of U.S. citizens - 21 million people of voting age - do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such a card.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
That's a lot more than that.
Students, who are considered to be voters who vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their institution-issued photo ID cards.
However, the same States allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures clearly aim to limit Hispanic voting.
It turns out that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers sponsored legislation in 2011 that abolished voter registration on election day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the general election of 2004, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the number of new voters registered in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states to reduce the voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33 percent of those who voted early were African-American, while African-Americans made up only 13 percent of the state's electorate.
The same was true of Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of citizens voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, made up only 46% of the early voters.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
However, the new rules will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the pro-democracy nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed for the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on participation rates.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Prostate cancer screening: pass the test or not?
The fact is that the APS test could sometimes produce false results, with false negative or false positive results, which would lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
Which makes even more hesitant men who are already reluctant to take screenings.
Pass the test or not?
We asked two experts for their advice.
In the US studies, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and to have strong recommendations.
Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had a screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that you have a 30 to 40 percent higher chance of getting metastases if you're not screened.
So I recommend testing from age 50, or from age 40, if you have a direct relative who has had prostate cancer before.
African-American men are also at higher risk.
The key is to make the right decision once you've been diagnosed with cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are lazy.
We really need to make the patient understand the extent of their cancer risk, by offering them the possible options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect long-term life, and instead opting, in these cases, for active disease surveillance.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We'll suggest active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we'll offer them treatment.
More and more, the criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated are being precisely determined.
So I still recommend passing the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to decide whether or not to pass it.
Movember, in collaboration with the International Urological Society, has developed a tool that assesses the pros and cons of the APS test.
The document can be downloaded (for now, a translation will be available soon) at: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing illness
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for cancer.
Despite advances in research, adopting good lifestyle habits remains the best way to reduce the risk of suffering from it.
It's estimated that if everyone ate well and moved around enough, we could prevent 30 percent of cancers.
"If no one else smoked, that rate would rise to at least 50 percent", says André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
However, it is estimated that about 10 percent of cancers are caused by heredity.
Many remain completely unexplained.
The Canadian Cancer Society maintains that the fight against smoking remains a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Cigarette smoking is linked to 85 percent of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for many others.
It's a huge health hazard for people.
"There are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec today", lamented spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouraging facts: Ten years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer has fallen by half.
Weight
Obesity and obesity also contribute to the onset of the disease, according to the CCS.
They would increase the risk of breast, colon and rectal, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancers.
"Research shows that regular lifelong physical activity protects against colon cancer", it adds.
Food
The body also recommends limiting red meat consumption.
Too much of it increases the risk of colorectal cancer.
The carcasses are also, and they should be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"The latter can damage the cells of the body and lead to the development of cancer", it is explained.
Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the link between vitamin supplements and cancer.
However, their research is not conclusive at this time.
Studies on vitamin E are contradictory, according to the CCS.
While one of them saw a decrease in the risk of prostate cancer, another saw an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer is also not clearly established.
Mr. Beaulieu also stresses the importance of discussing his concerns and family history with his doctor.
"Getting a screening test doesn't give you cancer".
The Higgs boson is decortified
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson is involved in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, just that.
And then it's the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model -- our best, or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but that hasn't been empirically observed yet.
But physicists are still not entirely sure that it's actually the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that we're holding a genuine new particle, and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely certain.
But suppose it's actually the Higgs, since the odds of being wrong seem slim, and let's see what it's all about.
There is, in this world of the underworld, a inevitable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a strange world, it also has a similar law: Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" consisting largely of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And the other is the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything -- at least not for this principle, which means they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) Berkeley Laboratories' The Particle Adventure site: mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the "force particles", through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson is somehow related.
These bosons, it must be pointed out here, are not all such exotic beasts as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this column, it is because of an extraordinary banality of a boson: the photon, or "light particle", that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at that precise location, much like a rock thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" gives rise to an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
It's the same with the Higgs boson, except that it's almost the same as another field, the Higgs field, which has to be "disrupted" for that boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, kind of like it's a frozen pond whose surface can only be covered by a very large rock.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN's -- the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! -- to reach such energies.
An analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like the photon, yours) don't.
What is the "benefit" of all this research, Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and predictions of MS.
There are many who would like to see some of them, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physique" and close some holes in the Model.
It is true that the universe still has enormous flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (again!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (again!).
But we haven't found such discrepancies at CERN until now.
The impact
The impact of this research on Mr and Mrs All World's daily life is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
Note: In the early 1960's, the pioneers of laser at Bell Laboratories had no idea what revolution their work would trigger.
They were looking at scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle has already told us - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - the laser was originally seen as a "lab gadget".
I mean, imagine.
And then, applications can also come from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 while working on optics.
This sensor, although not originally intended, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras worldwide, and won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This doesn't mean, of course, that LHC activities will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With its Commission to Die with Dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
But much remains to be done in this vital area.
The duty tried to look at it more closely.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that was eating him had left him with two years of rest.
"They gave me five years to live, I did seven", he said, half-figure half-raisin, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois hospice in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it", he says.
The disease is working its way up: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone, even eating alone.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he accepts help to eat, resigned.
He's brave, he even smiles, he talks to strangers around him, they bring him his medicine, they offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating", he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for the disease.
"In our lifetime, we learn that a man urinates standing up", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
To go back to the childhood stage is, for some people, an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept regression, he notes.
For many palliative care workers, there are great moments in the heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois paediatric care home all have cancer.
They have a life expectancy of up to three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no wishes in life anymore", she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting for her son's last visit from Italy in the coming days.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provides physical care and nutrition assistance.
It's palliative care, which you give when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there are 11 700 people in a palliative care bed.
It's very little when you know we all die one day.
Here life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the home.
Whether it's physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
We'll accept oral care with brandy or Pepsi on death row, as requested.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died last night.
This morning, it's her son who's gonna finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help our loved ones as much as we help our patients", says Nathalie Savard, director of health care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days go by, but they're not the same.
Alongside a 93-year-old man enjoying his last family gathering in the courtyard, well-closed in his pillows while a drink is being made in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife, and two young children, after trying to survive.
"For six months now, there are still three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under 45", says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their homes, 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate pain when a patient reaches the terminal stage of his life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this large shortage of health care in Quebec that has caused many palliative care doctors to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October a manifesto, signed by the leaders of the palliative care community, including Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
She says that recently, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room in great pain, without any relief.
I'm afraid some patients are asking to die just because they're not getting the right care.
And at the same time, many oncologists are sticking to their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helen Richard's survival prospects were already low when she abandoned the stressful chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist I was stopping treatment, she said she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
She told me I was done!
No Almighty Care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank their caregivers for not acceding to their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not necessarily all-powerful in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are reported to be reluctant to receive pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often use paleo-medication, which is used to put the patient back to sleep until the time of death, either sporadically or permanently.
You can't pretend you don't hear that part of the pain anymore.
More and more, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase, "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to euthanasize me", it means, "I want to be relieved".
