With Bitcoin, Pay and Sell Without Banks
The opposite is true of current currency exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often happens in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, which is made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure BitTorrent-like exchange protocol, which allows for peer-to-peer file exchange.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as gifts or as a means of payment.
After reaching a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, the price of bitcoin fell to $2 five months later, before falling back to around $10 today (the prices are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive compared to the global exchange of real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is distinct from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", which are used to progress in a video game that is won by playing or can be bought (and sometimes exchanged in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and processes the trade.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both bookkeepers, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two email addresses in the form of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged are well kept in the public ledger, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction into this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that extra line.
This is a file hashing phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter, unique digital fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "making" the whole.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes can easily verify that it's the right one.
The transaction is then inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, for fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided in half regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
So the number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundred millionth, leaving room for...
The difficulty of the challenge is also highlighted with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has had its ups and downs.
Web sites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and bitcoin deposits stolen.
"The flaw used is not the protocol itself", says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Weight-bearing actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
