Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, "giant soldiers" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who also authored an educational book on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its Paytunia system is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which is cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they need is an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point", he predicts.
The ECB also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, if the currency succeeds.
