They are guarded by the ancient city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris, which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
Legend has it that Noah built his ark here and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially enjoy walking along narrow alleys named after the zodiac signs.
They say if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to your sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will meet newlyweds who have come to take pictures from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesar's city, King Herod's, you can wander into the Roman theater, "conquering" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
