If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your English. About 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to euros, since they are easily exchanged for shekels (today 1 dollar equals 3.8 shekels).
The main transportation in the city is by bus, but Jerusalem has a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations that can connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost like an underground funicular.
The cost of all public transport is 6 shekels and you can make changes for 1:30 hours.
In Israel, Jewish tradition requires that the Sabbath be observed on Saturday.
From Friday evening to Saturday sunset, markets, shops and public transportation cease operations.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only casher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
There are a multitude of dishes made with lamb and beef, soups and desserts made with coconut milk, but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, various sauces, ground chicken peas, falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
