At this time, no one can predict whether this wave will increase in intensity or slowly exhale.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Alongside the rise in the modest salaries of Walmart and fast food chains, the organizers of the protests are seeking to get unions formed.
This sector is not covered by the trade union movement at the moment.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week, after Thanksgiving, on "Black Friday", when a torrential downpour of balances swept through America, sometimes triggering scandals.
On that day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs to organize strike picketing with unions and leftist activists in the company's stores whose products are aimed at middle- and lower-class consumers.
Walmart sells everything from blankets to hunting rifles to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
On average, products are 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That's why many low-paid employees at Walmart shop only at their workplace.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
Critics say Walmart can afford to sell its products cheaply, especially because of the low wages of its employees.
They also complain of difficult working conditions, such as the lack of lifting cars or portable scanners.
Participants in the "Black Friday" protests demanded a pay rise, they complained that the price of the company's medical insurance had increased from $30 to $100 a month.
For the basic worker at Walmart who makes $9.5 an hour, that's a sum he can't afford.
Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley show that if Walmart raised the average hourly wage to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That's 1.1 percent more than he's spending now.
If Walmart were to transfer all the pay increases to consumers, every run in the store would cost them 46 cents more.
They'll spend only $12.39 more in one year than they do now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did no harm to the group.
The "Black Friday" continued in stores from 8pm to midnight the next day and Walmart sold 5,000 items per second over that period.
His coffers made a total of 100 million transactions for Black Friday.
The company's spokesman Dan Fogleman said in an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post website that "less than five" Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest was only "an operation like many others" by the organizing union.
"Next client!"
The protests continued this week in New York City and were not about Walmart stores (in this progressive city, they are not very popular, so they are not yet established there) but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's announces they're selling billions of servings and then they don't even give you sick leave and pay you for honest work!
Jumaane Williams, member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage required by federal and New York law is $7.25 per hour.
Fast-food companies increase it over time, but on average, its basic employees earn $8.90 an hour in New York.
No one touches them less than they do in this town.
I don't think it's possible for me to live with that kind of money in New York.
There was a time when almost a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald's after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw it as their main source of income or wanted to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald's employees who complain about having to live with that salary and sometimes having to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, on the Wall Street Journal forum, there are comments that it's irresponsible to have children if you don't know what you're going to feed them.
Protesters who started the movement Thursday at 6:30 a.m. near McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue demanded that cashiers and fast food chefs be paid a minimum of $15 an hour, more than double the current minimum wage.
They also called for the creation of trade unions in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing the protest and punishing union protesters by firing or firing.
However, administration rarely makes life easier for them.
For a union, catering fast food is still a difficult task, and for concrete reasons.
One of the main reasons is the extraordinary rotation of staff.
They disagree.
Other tumultuous protests were held near several other fast food chains.
The highlight of the protest was the midday rally near McDonald's in Times Square with the intervention of several local Democratic politicians, including Jumaane Williams, a city councillor, who said: "McDonald's announces that they sell billions of servings and after that they don't even give you sick leave and pay you for the honest work you've done!"
The protesters were supported by other prominent New York Democrats, including mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio who said that "we all need to support fast food workers so they get the fair pay and economic well-being every New Yorker deserves.
The New York Times described this event as the largest fast food industry event in its history.
But only a few hundred people took part, not all of them fast food workers, who employ tens of thousands of people in New York City.
It is difficult to say at this time whether this spark of mass movement will make small ones.
"At the moment, the only way to fool the brain is to trick the brain"
Lately, fans of new technology have become accustomed to seeing augmented reality through special glasses.
Google first unveiled its current model at its annual conference this summer, and in November it was reported that Microsoft had filed for the patent.
However, it appears from an interview with the director of the interactive 3D technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge lab, Shahram Izadi, that for the company's scientists, glasses are already a thing of the past.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands, by creating virtual open spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group does?
- We're working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we're trying to broaden the boundaries of that interaction.
Humanity as a whole has been left with pixels on flat screen and sometimes touch screen for the time being.
We want to look at five to 10 years ahead and guess what radical changes will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox is sold today without Kinect because everyone is interested in command by gesture.
- What else is in store for us?
- Although the Kinect has rendered physical interaction, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has been improved (the system receives more data), but the performance, for now, not really.
We're trying to change that and we're working on really 3D imaging systems that work on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to bring the computer world out into our own, into the physical world, make it more tangible.
However, this requires not only identifying the user but also the space around him.
So we can complement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And first, let's get rid of these stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think of the voice command ?
She's appreciated, but isn't she overrated?
The question of confidentiality arises because we do not always want to inform others of our actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of computer interaction is good, but each in its own niche.
For example, when we were ordering the devices in public places, we had a project where we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discrete, limited gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera but by a wristband that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean, "the one"?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this can?
You would do it with words and gestures.
- I usually only talk.
- Oh, it's going to be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or can't do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think very soon we'll have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, they produce a pretty good resolution in depth and that's very important.
- If we're interested in your work on the Xbox Kinect sensors, what's not to love about modern cameras?
Are they lacking resolution, depth, or something else?
- Basically, it's the current generation we're building on in our work on 3D recognition.
Obviously, it would be good to get about 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to the latter, all the current technologies are pretty good, adding to the work of algorithm designers.
The resolution must be kept in mind for the X and Y axes, but also for the Z axes.
Speed is also very important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s really isn't enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche of our Redmond lab gave the touch of the sensors a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 μs, with the current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
I'd really need a camera like that in my work, but not requiring touch, to get more frames a second.
- But shouldn't we increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three cameras, one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second one is a reflected signal receiver.
And the third camera is actually a regular field of view sensor.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
Many cameras could solve this problem...
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to the Kinect, play with the camera curve and see how it could help define locations.
- As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not shown its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that from the perspective of the everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most promising platforms?
Of course, walking around with your hands up all the time with a smartphone is not practical, but here's what I think: the best option would be a "transitional" augmented reality that would allow you to move from a cloud platform to a smartphone.
Glasses are a very personal device, and that's what makes them strong (personal elements are the only ones you see) and at the same time their weakness: Augmented reality from glasses won't allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that manipulating virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the common mortal.
There is one problem that those who oppose this idea point to: there is no sense of touch!
The hands can't feel anything!
What answers is your group preparing for this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth one might very well be the addition of touch sensations.
At the moment, one of the interesting techniques is using the second hand as a picture medium.
It's a perfect record of pressure!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give palpability to these "air images": for example, interference by several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is and which gives you the feeling, for the moment, of a breath of air on the tips of your fingers.
There are also wristbands that affect the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a working axis with perspective.
- And you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think he feels what he should normally feel when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
There is still a task below which it will take a long time to work hard on: how to make someone who is physically in a very narrow space think they are walking in an almost infinite open space - we are working on the concepts of race carpets (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
At the moment, we can only fool the brain with a medium, and there are still many years of work to do.
That's what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
