Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Space shuttle caravans with landers on board set off in search of a planet of relief.
To save humanity, a big question arises: How can we keep our species alive in a weightless state or on a life-saving planet?
I don't think there's much to choose from.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, even if only by hypothesis.
"It's Venus and Mars", says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If Mars is more suitable for life, the surface temperature on Venus is 500 degrees.
You can only live there at very high altitudes or on the orbit of Venus... in space.
We started to take an interest in the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, we were experimenting on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit were no different from the terrestrial varieties.
Then we put insects, small, breeding drosophilic flies, into orbit.
In 1979, sperm whales were sent into space to see how an embryo grows in weight.
You get a perfectly normal chicken out.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is that the chicken needs to find a support, get on its feet and start moving", explains Vladimir Sychev, director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medicinal Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
Without any support, the chicks moved in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chickens were not responding to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die within four days.
"We had to close our eyes twice and then we gave up because it was simply impossible to work with them there", explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was launched into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, Bion will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, we have not discovered anything supernatural.
"It was still biosatellites, and then it's the only experiment", observed Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, reproduction is not yet possible directly in space.
It's not a small matter.
The animals lose their normal environment and are unable to fulfill their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, humans are capable of doing so, in principle.
Homo sapiens has abstract thinking, is capable of creating a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not done for ethical reasons.
But women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is what mankind has most in value.
Our whale flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would survive a flight into space.
If she could have had a baby after the robbery.
"No one answered that question", explains Vakhtang Vatchnadzé, a retired rocket and space scientist.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Terechkova, gave birth to a baby girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut, Svetlana Savitskaya, after having been in orbit twice and even worked in an off-road environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it is dangerous even during orbital flight", concludes the Soviet Union's hero and Russian hero, the pilot and cosmonaut Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet, humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection, and the creation of artificial gravity.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonaut Training Centre: a mandatory step in the preparation for flight.
Here, with zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train for off-road excursions.
Water mimics weight.
While the water is comfortable for adults but a strange environment, for infants it is their real element.
The little amphibians seem to confirm that life on Earth originated in the ocean.
As the baby develops in the lymphatic fluid of the mother's womb for about nine months, it is easier for him to get used to the water.
This makes sense, in principle, because from birth to first bathing, it takes only two weeks.
"It's very little to forget", explains Marina Aksenova, a swimming instructor for infants.
In a nutshell, if for the newborn baby, weight is a more natural condition, the woman needs gravity, weight strength.
When the baby is overweight, the muscles of the abdomen and pelvis atrophy very quickly, and the baby's ability to push is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on birth simulators.
Of course, you can prepare a delivery in a special room, the woman will be able to get it out.
"And then?" asked Valeriy Poliakov, inviting us to think about this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
If the body does not feel the earth's pull, it cannot form the skeleton or the muscular system.
You can't dress a baby like an adult with a special training suit.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experiment we would consider in this case by imagining a child being born in a foreign environment will result in a disabled child returning to Earth, completely unfit", predicts Igor Pestov, Director of the Committee for Bioethics at the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
The birth of children in space is still a matter of theory.
However, in time this will become a reality when the Earthlings travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the home of their spaceship-born offspring.
The head of the ISC (Supreme Financial Control Institute) said: "The control of the pseudo-independent work (in Czech 'Svarc system') has failed because of politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation but is lagging behind in its application.
This was stated by Miloslav Kala, the vice president of the Higher Financial Control Institute in an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be just and I think that's what we lack", Kala said in his commentary on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice the approach of Petr Nečas to the "Svarc system".
Mr Prime Minister recently said that the SDGs are not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls; so is it allowed or prohibited ?
"The law must be enforced in some way, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an inspection authority from going to demand compliance with the law", says Kala.
At the meeting of the Committee on Auditors in the Chamber of Deputies you referred to a Czech-German draft in which the public procurement legislation of these two countries was compared.
What was it specifically about?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation and practice itself follow it.
We have put all this together and although this inspection procedure is not yet complete, we have found some very interesting differences: in general speaking, our legislation may be 'more stringent and of better quality', but, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to develop ever more detailed rules but that it is necessary to focus on the very application of the law.
How can this project help you in concrete terms and what will be the result for you?
This kind of joint control should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, lower and improve the thresholds when this has no real positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the item at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering the market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those who look for flaws in it will find far more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems concerning the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is there an institution similar to our ISC or a different way of organizing?
As regards institutions, the Bundesrechnungshof, like the ISC, operates there in a similar manner, and it also has a slightly different board, but these two institutions operate essentially in a similar way.
The competencies are also similar to a certain extent, with a slight contrast to our system: Germany is a federal structure and therefore has similar accounts at the level of the various Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which in our country corresponds to state resources.
The public funds managed by the regions and municipalities in our country are controlled at the level of the Länder' accounts.
Is the national legislation simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model but it cannot be said that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, I'm sure not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country which we consider a model also faces a whole series of problems.
Otherwise, they would have no advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As regards national legislation, what has the amendment to the public procurement law meant for you as an institution?
This amendment has not yet had an impact on our control operations, as it has come into force relatively recently.
Since we're doing a post-examination, we have to count on a delay.
Our comments concern only the process of preparing future checks - we have launched a new 'mismanagement risk detection' tool which has been used to identify almost 14 000 public procurements - and these changes will of course be felt, because thresholds have been changed and the conditions for certain types of tender procedures have been changed and so on.
So do you consider the adoption of this law more of an advantage or an added burden to the administration?
I think this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more stringent and they cannot be respected.
Already under the previous regulation, the provider (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) obliged the controlled entities to accept that any infringement of the market law constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really useful to make the law more stringent in this way?
No, not like that, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal mistakes without impacting the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what's the solution?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently the Prime Minister said that the SDGs would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called Švarc system - what does that mean?
Is the Švarc system banned or authorized?
The law must be enforced in some way, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going to inspect and demand compliance with the law.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and allow it", but he can't say we're going to act like nothing happened.
The market law has relatively strict rules on the formalities to be carried out, precisely to protect the tender.
But it is also tragic that a tenderer is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law can never be perfect, but the application of it must be just and I think that's what we lack.
