Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed took part in a number of ESA projects.
However, Poland's journey to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, enthusiastic Poles were working on spaceflight; they did not always get along.
I would like to recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw on December 6, 1933, during which he presented ideas from his groundbreaking book "An Introduction to Astronomy".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a major proponent of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of astronomy, and his contribution was rewarded by the fact that one of the craters on the Moon's hidden face was named after him.
As early as 1925 a dredge was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, we don't know who wrote this project or the details of it.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to propel or to brake the drill.
The only known information about this drill is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the preserved documents that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of German troops, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of operation, the war began and its activities were terminated.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
A company was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problème, which contained four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronomy.
By this time, artificial satellites had already been launched, and it was clear that space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and from the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM Meteorological Rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This 1,800-meter-range rocket was 80 centimetres long and weighed just under five kilograms.
Later an improved version, RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was about a foot long and probably weighed 11.5 kilograms.
The next prototype should have been capable of performing concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all the development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965 succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
The rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the aeronautical institute, and the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland joined COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and that a national COSPAR committee was established two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut in this programme.
