It is part of a realistically conceived political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, a betrayal - as, for example, in the Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The scenes are sequential: documentary-style footage of Tehran (subtitled footage shows iconic photographs of the time of the events and how, thanks to these photos, the same situations were retranscribed in the film, there are no major differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with men in costumes discussing the situation around conference tables, in the halls and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in remarkable ways.
He was ridiculed as an actor, became a respected director, and his acting career stopped arousing ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the darkly-themed police drama Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The Town (2010).
It is also the first of Affleck's films not to take place in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his early films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real events; the initial sequence of the embassy fall is impressive in clarity that also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is being written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director must have settled for a subject that in fact offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
It is very successful, sometimes adding elements to reality and the result is not always so elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is turned away by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway is quite a drag).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipative nature, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-workers, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are far from alone in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it is seen with moderate interest, appreciating the 70s's re-making and style.
He's drawing the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the job.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circuses
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a public survey of the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch the competition for the most absurd regulations or ideas from the "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU is recently considering adopting a quota of 40 percent women for the management of major European companies has been the basis of our decision", said Patrik Nacher, the survey's organizer, to the Právo newspaper.
The Commission has already taken a number of measures to ensure that the Community's financial resources are not used to finance the work of the European Parliament.
Until now, however, women have been given the advantage of life insurance rates because they objectively represent a lower risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of the 'EU workshop'.
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013", Nacher informed.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the requirement to add bio-components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the prohibition on using reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the Directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticism has also been expressed in the past against the actual prohibition of the use of the term 'tasting butter' or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional bulbs.
The quality bananas must be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose claims are usually defended in Brussels by a State or group of States (the Czech Republic is thus currently imposing the claims of its banks by threatening to exercise its veto power).
The interests of pressure groups are also driven, for example, by the fact that bananas in the Union must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an 'abnormal curvature'.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was only harmonizing non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
The rules on fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite opposition from some States, claiming that existing directives lead to food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to last year's EU regulation that inflatable balloons must have a warning that children under 8 years of age should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU referred to a US survey that found balloons to be the leading cause of childhood deaths from choking among toys.
A similar restriction applies to children under 14 years of age when blowing in fair trumpets.
We have weird ideas here too.
The following rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this theme to Greece, anyone holding an official position within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In this investigation, in collaboration with the Laissez Faire association of liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com mentioned, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the Union Regulation on the volume of food reserves in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum food stocks that could be in the Czech Republic on the day of our accession.
The Czech Republic then exceeded the volume of canned mushrooms and was therefore subject to a heavy fine.
The organisers of the survey found it interesting to pay money to some countries because they do not have access to the sea and to grant grants to apply for grants.
These ideas, however, did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"Not having a sea is a handicap.
We will ask the European Union for a refund.' This was the view expressed in the autumn of 2004 by the then Minister of Agriculture, Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
He argued that, as a result of our wheat production, and following so-called 'interventionist' purchases, the State had left with full stocks which it had to export.
Palas said the EU should have paid us millions of euros because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
Finally, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech demand and organised a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
The grants for the granting of grants were proposed to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development under Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU) and were to be used to draw up applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU says: "Weird regulations are rare".
While regulations often attract criticism in the Member States, many experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the Union's functioning and its overall development are worthy of praise.
The problem is even more serious, for example, according to experts, the problem of using EU grants for projects which have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration but which have been imposed by the Member States during budgetary negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a struggle that it does not always win) is stirring strong emotions among the Czechs.
After six years of fighting the Germans and the Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky", and our producers had to replace the name "Tuzemský rum" with the name "Tuzemák" for the name "Tuzemský rum" that dates back to the 19th century.
Only products made from cane sugar alcohol, not beet sugar, may bear the name rum.
The official list of EU registered products includes today world-famous cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, Lübeck cheese or Parma ham, Karlovy Vary biscuits, Pohořelice and Třeboň carp, and Žatec hop (Žatecký chmel).
Pardubický perník and Hořické trubičky are also proud of their Community brand.
People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, how do we plan on running for president?
It's not about being a senator or president that matters to me.
If everything worked out in our country, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
But I can't stand to see the country being plundered over the last 20 years, that thieves are not under lock and key, and taxes and retirement age are increasing.
I had no ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, then I try to come up with a solution to change it.
And as I am over forty years old and an independent, nonpartisan, I have no other choice to influence the situation than to run for president or for senator.
You entered the Senate but you quickly set off for the Castle.
Is this how you turn your backs on those who have chosen you?
I always said I'd fight for the castle according to the results of the Senate election.
Later, I made it clear that if I were elected senator, I would run for president.
My purpose is not function, it's just a tool to make my vision come true.
That's why I need the greatest influence and the broadest mandate.
The problem is not only that as a nation we rally at the bar or in front of our TV station, but we also cough up those who try to make a difference.
And the press is also one that is damaging people's reputations and confusing freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
For example, I was accused of bribing journalists or of being a counselor to Jiří Paroubek.
Let's get to your visions.
You have begun the fight for the Castle with the themes of political material and criminal liability as your battle horse and retroactive tax returns in excess of 20 million.
You must change the law to that end.
As president, you don't have that kind of power, and only the Senate as a whole can pass laws.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When as a citizen I pushed for tourist guide activities to be a liberal profession, I won.
The problem is the politics: when someone comes from the left or the right with a good project, it is knowingly rejected and it delays citizens.
As an independent, non-partisan, I am much more likely to get the support of all parliamentary parties.
I have the advantage of being able, without categorization and partisan dogma, to take from each party what is best for our country and implement it.
Do you consider yourself a right-wing or a left-wing man ?
From a Czech point of view, I feel like people are putting me on the left.
For me, whether it's a little left or right doesn't really matter.
For me, the important thing is that we move forward.
What matters to me is not that people are left or right, but that people are brought together.
I always support any solution that contributes to the common good, even if it is proposed by the Communist Party or the SDGs, and I am equally impartial against bad ideas.
Do you get angry when someone says you're a populist?
But what you said doesn 't prove it ?
When you develop a business plan in a company, you also have a certain optimal purpose and vision.
You're trying to get close to it.
Some may call this populism, but all the proposals I'm talking about have been applied by the world and recognized experts have spoken about it.
But without parliamentary support, all you have left is slogans.
You won't survive long in politics with that.
Do you think that if you go to see people and talk to them, you will be able to, for example, impose material and criminal liability?
I don't have a choice.
I have to convince politicians, journalists and the public and try to rally them to my side to impose it.
If I were elected president, it would not be a problem to broadcast live on television my request to the presidents of parliamentary parties to legislate on the material and criminal liability of politicians, officials, judges and prosecutors.
Then they might have to explain why they don't want to.
When there is a strong personality who identifies the abuse, it will be possible to put pressure on the political scene.
Take, for example, the direct presidential election, which was achieved through public pressure.
I admit, without question, that I am an amateur, not a genius or an intellectual.
I'm trying to find allies for my views and visions.
I just got into politics and I'm trying to get the majority support for my program.
I'm trying to move things forward, and if it doesn't work, I'll quit in six years and go back to the private sector.
It's like Okamura is going to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know that one person can't make a difference, so I went to a number of personalities and asked them to run for the Senate as well.
I met Radim Jančura, but he refused because of the amount of work.
I at least supported investigative journalist Jana Lorencová who exposed the oil scams.
I introduced myself because people are really unhappy but now I'm hesitant.
Sixty percent of the people did not vote and most of the people who did did did so voted for a representative of the establishment.
In the Senate, we're just two independents.
The people have elected a Senate that can hardly impose change.
I will, however, fight for my vision, for example the direct election of mayors and regional prefects.
Are you considering starting your own party?
