The architects at MVRDV prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination.
"I find this building funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, tells us, "Yes, this building is indeed beautiful".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everybody has the Internet, an iPad, and e-books.
No one is willing to go to one of those shady libraries now, is that right?
Spijkenisse, a dormant town that has nothing to do with the gates of Rotterdam, has a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
To give some neurons back to the brain, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small, painted concrete miniatures.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
The city officials realized that there was only one way to get back to the statistics - to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam architects' office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mindful and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual flegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a laughing smile on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, confused and shouldering, Maas, the shameless, packed his favorite books in order of size to make them a pyramid, and finished his speech backed by activist arguments with a "dear fellow!"
Here's my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the $30 million mountain burst to the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project which also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 houses.
In early November, the book mountain was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dull little village, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunningly ugly town hall, whose white façades suggest that they house a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to Reading
First impression: Eldorado from the book with cheese bell.
While an elevator takes you to the heart of the cliff, the real joys of reading and architecture are opened to you as you step on the floor of the building and discover its topography.
The interior, made entirely of glass, is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant refractors speak the language of municipal public squares.
The atmosphere in the city is perfect.
We're already looking for the public banks, the dogs and the little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere there are books, books and books.
"Usually, the library beams are along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal", explains Willy Maas.
We completely upended the classical spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the book mountain has been skillfully laid out: in the center are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental center and the building's technical center.
A special beauty lies in the black beams of the library, which are sometimes lined with walls, sometimes with balustrades, sometimes with stairwells.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unfamiliar materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse Municipality, in a response to the Standard.
We have found ad hoc agricultural waste in a farmhouse.
In the Netherlands, a millimeter-thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and it saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons and then thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time, in such quantities, into plates four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes colour and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
Nearly 500 metres away, the literary café offers a breathtaking view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute most to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model ecological project", Trouborst says.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun shines only briefly inside, even on good weather days.
The thick wooden beams mounted in a wrong direction from the glass facade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the septic computer scientist mentioned above, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already here.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even described the Boekenberg as "Spijkenisse's finally found soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure helped fill the gaps in the library that had not yet been filled (now 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are pouring out all over the place.
According to architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library".
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows their book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for the decorations".
This is how MVRDV has developed into the master discipline known in professional jargon as "creating an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role".
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a difficult political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose not to.
Why would you?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, since it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but not to be too critical of Israel.
In the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have difficulty in taking a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy as it were defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
The lack of coherent and common policies within the Union is also complicating the situation.
The Germans are therefore facing off on several fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I believe they are still trying to find that role, but they are on the path to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for Germans?
It is willing to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that Germany's foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, and therefore by its exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other great powers, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and its abstention from the UN vote?
Germany has, first of all, important trade opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
This is why Berlin must be careful not to strike public opinion but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, as it is not a one-sided relationship.
But this is at least a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany damage its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain from important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans understand Germany's position perfectly.
I therefore believe that the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
The United States, however, has declared its veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and most European countries?
There have always been differences because of the domestic political scene in the United States.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll notice that Obama is far from overwhelmed with enthusiasm about Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany have difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
It is clear that it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today this is not the case.
They cannot therefore be part of a larger political line and must assert their unique position.
This is what they are doing now in the euro area.
In my view, Germany will in future play a role as a locomotive and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of its relations with Israel.
That question has always been tricky.
But I think the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that will further their independence.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does she still have trouble taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to this, it is always uncomfortable and for obvious reasons the country is still having difficulty playing a greater role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German sentiments are expressed.
It's not easy for the Germans.
In fact, it's still the same problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with very different neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only decreasing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this gap, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
And even if they don't like it, even if they don't like it, even if they don't like it, and they don't appreciate it, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trade mark protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are world-renowned brands.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark is thus protected in such a way that the company bearing the trade mark's name cannot bring a complaint.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd win.
"It is increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", explains Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a firm specializing in infringement of property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my desk.
Impersonators only need a few additional letters to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies also have legal copyrights, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sportswear.
Pattloch opens a ledger containing the records made at the Beijing Trademark Office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, a designation that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually nothing but counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's case is different: his agents are charged with addressing the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese say "Bang Mingpai", a family name.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
This is the term used for women who marry rich men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend", Pattloch demands.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the reputational damage is enormous".
The financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially in the case of expensive flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis firm CLSA, China is the world's third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market, with an annual turnover of EUR 15 billion.
However, it is not easy to remove dubious trademark registrations from the register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports on trials in which the court rejected the complaint because after a long period of time the criticised denomination had become a "true market".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the beach resort, because it would damage his trademark in China.
In this area, sometimes the law of the jungle is the dominant one.
Famous cases also involve graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler had lost a legal battle against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought out the concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That's why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo acquirer, used a blue and white logo that resembled BMW's logo before the dispute was resolved and Geely had to modify it.
The Lacoste fashion house had lost to the beaches of Hong Kong and Singapore who had turned the famous crocodile's gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits, however, that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the Office was reportedly moved from a "work situation of emergency to a normal situation" last year.
The number of untreated opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 cases of this type were reported to have been closed, a 75% increase from the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 procedures remain pending at the office.
The cost of doing so
As often in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and it means that China is for the tenth time in a row at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal marks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office reportedly had 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each registration brought in an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs far more, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg illustrates.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese beach house.
The Germans were able to obtain a suspension of the illegal manufacture of vehicle components.
However, the copycat retained its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"It's our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany", explains Hanno Wentzler, chairman of Freudenberg Chemical Speciality in Munich.
The trademark office therefore rejected the objection of the Munichers.
Freudenberg won the following two cases, but the opposing party still struggles to this day.
The Warning Is On
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
However, he adds: "The procedure is long, time-consuming, and costly".
It is also difficult to assess the internal costs, and the Archives Department has even had to review the records of the last hundred years to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered the opposing party a "big six-figure euro" to settle the dispute.
"That's how we see what it means to us", says Wentzler.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to extend even to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region were to ensure that the unprotected trademarks are exploited.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer wanted to register Freudenberg's name in Germany for a shoe and leather company.
