Prosecutors tried to show Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being behind the largest leak of classified information in the history of the U.S. military -- missed many occasions to complain about the mistreatment he claims he suffered during his military detention.
During a counter-interrogation with Manning during a preliminary hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The counter-interrogation -- during a hearing, the defense filed a motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the seizure was done under very difficult conditions and was a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning expressed his desire to commit suicide while in custody.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
The documents were later published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms the officers had filled out after meeting with Manning during his detention at the Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum-security prison confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment provided by his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in prison was "very professional" overall.
The forms do not mention any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns orally about certain problems and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record the problems mentioned.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn't mean I hadn't raised problems", Manning said.
Military Judge Colonel Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the Special Commission that met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating a "risk of injury".
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know I was fine, and I wanted this status to be removed... so that I could enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view", Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps Military Prison at Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered suicide while in Kuwait and once passed out from the heat.
He added that not being told what was coming to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was confined to Camp Arafjon, to this cage", Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least nine hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, a blanket, tongs, clothes, and glasses.
He tried to stay on the move, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
