The hardest job in the world: human mules in Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian volcano-bearers risk their lives and health carrying 70 kilograms of sulfur through steep stone paths.
There are people who work for hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulfuric gas from the earth's interior solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large, weighing about 70 kilograms of sulfur, he places them in two bamboo baskets and carries them on his shoulders along the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters, but weary climbers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle's pace, keeping their feet in balance and measuring them so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a wrong step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell deadly in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur extracted.
Once up there, they make their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little below at 1,850 meters.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, as it were, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (€5 cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since it is very common in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"Because we carry about 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) each trip", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes three hours and ends up exhausted, but that allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it may seem a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the fields.
"The income of miners is very high here, where coffee harvesting is paid 15,000 rupees (1,20 euros) a day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", says the carrier who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to her family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that in Indonesia is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and eyes irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on Kawah Ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto has asthma, difficulty breathing, constant coughing, and her eyes are irritated by the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
It's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'll work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French", he promises in more than acceptable English.
This friendly, intelligent young man, who is plagued by life, may be a tour guide, a waiter, or a hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy woodworking pattern with other carriers, rising every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur never ceases to gush at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the dark.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater, shining with a small lamp attached to his headset, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanised the extraction of sulphur to save costs and provides no equipment to the self-employed and weight-paid carriers.
They also do not receive a penny of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) in camera surcharge, in addition to the 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) that the park guards charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for animals, not humans", protested 42-year-old Madrusin, a fat-carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since he left school.
He can weigh up to 110 pounds and says he will work "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his three sons, ages 10 to 18.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of serious illnesses... in addition to their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53, can only carry 50 kilos.
Each day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away, through a goat trail filled with weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life", Unainik says, opening his mouth wide, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of five children, a 30-year-old, also works as a sulphur ship.
Time passes, but the continuing misery from generation to generation is one of the most difficult jobs in the world: the one done by the human mules of the Kawah Ljen volcano.
