He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post pictures of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would if I was angry or upset.
"Even though I know it's cyberbullying", he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, a professor of English and a licensed teacher in Education and Learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents, one must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a way to seek information but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed", she says.
The academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in education from Yale University and is the author of the book "Digital Natives and Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are themselves, children and young people who are born with technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them here, while we are learning ourselves", she says.
He adds that the subject is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined criterion on what is or is not to be disclosed, published or said at an age when they are not mature enough to do so".
"We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences", she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is to use questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it is useless", she says.
Then, list a few examples: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or would you like them to post a photo of you like a friend you posted?
Do you know what other people are saying about you?
When you identify party photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you're doing at any given moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they should act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, and it must be the same on social media", she says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and education advisor, says that it is vital that parents read the terms and conditions of social media carefully.
By understanding each of these terms, they will have a solid foundation for discussing with their children the implications of opening an online account.
"For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or published", he says.
Guardia says it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNSUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The sixth Presidency Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven delegates present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit was closed, then claimed that it would be posted from time to time on the Peruvian government website.
When they were asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by Peruvian President Ollante Humala in brief press releases.
The access of journalists to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the silent video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was aired in the press room.
The few reports among journalists were those given by press officers from some of the governments of the United Nations that were present at the meeting, except for the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency emailed the media with the summit's "final statement", but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document concluding the summit.
Last October Peru hosted the 3rd South American Arab Summit (SAAS) and, on this occasion, although press urged it, it did not publish the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
The official website of ASPA confirms that the document was published last March.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities tried to set up secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice which decided on a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the decision of the ICJ to hear the pleas of both parties in the Lima trial against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing today before this international court", President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been and will continue to be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of international disputes, treaties and courts", added President Piñera, shaking President Humala's hand, holding the flags of both countries.
The two presidents' confirmation that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact, which had agreed to submit to the decisions of the International Court of Justice, following a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from the UN since 2011 after the removal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that action lines for 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total investment of 17 million dollars.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of the United Nations would make "important strides to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of residence permit agreements".
He said that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organised crime, actions for better access to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not be a triumphal matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to foresee a better future for our people", concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 landmark projects that improve connectivity in South America, particularly in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", the Peruvian president said in a speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects were in Peru and were located on the cross-sectional axes of Peru's territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give details.
The final document also mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region, integrated and in good relations with its neighbours, was another theme discussed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before the regional meeting began that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico City next Saturday to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a decision of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", said President Santos.
"We will review all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will require a discussion with that country", he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", added President Santos.
President Santos and President Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday to witness the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, the summit will see the EU's Defence Ministers meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen defence dialogue and consensus in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of the UN, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru shall hold the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship", says Rafael Correa.
President Rafael Correa of Ecuador said today that the creation of a common citizenship was a goal for which "South America, in this case, should set an example for Europe".
President Correa, who attended the VI Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) in Lima, told Peruvian state television TV that Europeans "had killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they were almost a homeland".
In this sense, he defended the South American citizenship project encouraged by the member countries of the United Nations.
"The free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country must be achieved, as is already the case for the Andean Community members, but there are still reactionary areas that we want to make a thing of the past", he warned.
In addition, the Ecuadorian President supported the reconstitution of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the aim of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon States and taking into account the signatories of the San José Pact on Human Rights.
Those who are listening to us never compromise anything, on the contrary, we South Americans all signed it.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under US funding", he said, referring to Ecuador's political asylum granted to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa said he did not regret his decision, as he did not betray his own principles, but instead respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He concluded that at the time, "there were well-founded suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his trial would not be respected".
He also criticized the Swedish judiciary for requiring him to be interrogated in his country over an alleged sexual offence while "Swedish law itself allows videoconferencing, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa said there was a risk that Assange's mental and physical health would deteriorate.
"I haven't spoken to him since he's been in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a small lung problem, but nothing serious", said the Ecuadorian president.
It is possible that his physical and mental health may deteriorate by being confined to a small space without being able to exercise outdoors.
"It affects everyone's health", he concludes.
Correa reports that the asylum solution granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London, which would be the granting of a safe passage that would allow him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and European judicial authorities and he points out that he has been in talks in London to find a solution to the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
We are not negotiating with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been continuous discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, has launched a series of proceedings in different European courts", he said.
And he thinks "if Britain gives the exemption tomorrow, it'll be over".
And if Sweden, as its legislation allows, and as it has done in other cases, interviewed Mr Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or interviewed him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took this opportunity to reassert himself as a defender of press freedom and he said what he did not tolerate was "mediocrity, bad faith and lies that undermine freedom of expression".
"The greatest enemies of press freedom are not the evil or perverse politicians but the bad journalists who pay for greed, blackmail and extortion", he said.
He welcomed the fact that it was not the kind of journalists "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate Ecuador" and, rather than pushing for his re-election, "he would deepen the revolution to continue and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay within Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the body "must stand firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality, "it would destroy the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
Moreover, the Ecuadorian President considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty, "perfectly relevant".
At this time, this judgment is not being upheld.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
We must solve them as a whole to get past them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the proper resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile in the same court and said that it was "beneficial for Latin America to bring international cases if both countries agreed to accept a judgment as firm as it is".
Referring to the possibility of running for a third consecutive term in the future presidential election in Ecuador, he said he saw this opportunity "with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 primary, he would retire from public life.
On a personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as those in Ecuador, this socioeconomic poverty can only be solved through political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the guarantor of this eventual victory but we must accept that responsibility", he said.
If I win, it would be my last term as president and I will retire from politics.
If we ever lose, I'll lose too.
"It's my decision", he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a decline in the health status of President Chávez", he commented.
The Ecuadorian Head of State today attended the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) in Lima, which ended with a call for better regional integration to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS-related deaths are now the result of late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 when he was confirmed to have HIV.
"It's as if the sky had fallen on my head", he said, referring to the moment of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and started to inquire about it and his diligence was such that he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), where he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless".
Back then, having AIDS was death.
Today, it is possible to survive the syndrome and to have a good quality of life.
However, many people, unaware of their illness, still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "deleted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the world's AIDS outbreak, in all cases after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG HIV unit, referring to the fact that this information was validated in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system impairment patients had at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years for a CD4 rate of 200 and up to 50 years for those who reach a CD4 rate of 500.
Simply put, this means that for someone diagnosed with HIV at age 25, "as long as they remain under control, they can live without problems for up to 75 years", the scientist said.
To put this progress into context, it is important to note that the average life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years.
While mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in Mexico the number of people who died from AIDS has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the annual report of UNAIDS), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 died by May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral medicines has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
In the last 12 years at least, we've never run out of medicines, the problem is that patients get to very advanced stages because they don't know they're infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact that "nine out of ten patients arrive with an opportunistic infection, and the only way to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make early diagnoses and to do so, mass screening tests must be offered to all who request it".
Experts and members of the Jalisco State AIDS Prevention Council (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to take his screening test in a private laboratory simply because a friend had done so and that, despite his young age, he was already AIDS-positive and suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better I blow myself up three times a week", they say, "not my case".
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
So far, all his parents know is that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I am co-responsible, I take care of myself and the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help those who are afraid today, through his testimony, during the World AIDS Day march.
If they get tested, if they take risks, the sooner they know if they're HIV positive and the better, and if they've already been diagnosed, they need to know that you can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the average citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who embraced the cause of HIV.
And the greatest part is prevention.
"We have actually increased condom distribution in all places, before we were given one or two condoms, now we are given packages of one hundred condoms, which is fine, but as a result, some people still do not have access to condoms", he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are teenagers.
The question, "What are you going to do about it?" asked with sarcasm and valuable judgments by social workers, counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, the journalist assures.
He proposed a reorientation of this inefficient distribution; that condoms should not only be sold at the counter but also in the distributors of public toilets and in the places where young people go.
This is not about promoting promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González replied when asked if there would be a condom distribution in his administration.
"That's not how sex works, it's best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active", he said.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state is the fourth largest state in the country in the number of new cases and cumulative cases of AIDS and the 13th largest in the number of HIV patients.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are from the bloodstream and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for every recorded case, there are four or five people who are unaware of it.
