Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
Basketball world-trotting "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in connection with the field and, thanks to him, has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as much knowledge of the history of local basketball as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage sent him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a minor league player, national basketball player, manager and head of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s", recalls Reyes during a Primera Hora visit to his home in Bayamón, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life".
Reyes doesn't overdo it when he makes that claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia reminiscent of his unusual itinerary, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he cherishes most are those that remind him of his time as a player with the Vaqueros in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as the team's co-manager or manager.
"These were my best years, the ones I took the most advantage of because I was lucky enough to be in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967 onwards, whether as a manager, co-manager or manager.
This has been a satisfying time for many years, including the five championships from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over the team", says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was a former head coach at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, telling me, "I have a tough player for you, he's six feet tall.
Do you want it?"
That's how to start with Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse to me, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had let Bayamon win one championship, Gausse would help us try and win another.
He was happy with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only from a distance since in 1988 he was already the main manitou of the federation.
At the time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's responsibilities in the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-Olympic Games in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth and we should have won the bronze medal if that Canadian referee hadn't let us play the last game again, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She's one of the best, as was the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the U.S. team, which was pretty similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only made up of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the World Cup of 90 due to a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and a great joy in the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players suspended by the imposture of the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
No doubt about it, it's Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has ever dominated at this level as Piculín has.
And that's without taking into account his track record in the various leagues he played for.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team made up of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like the work Leo Arill does when I'm young.
What do you think is your greatest achievement in the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious period of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you have to do?
There are things I would have liked to have put in place, like the regionalisation of minor categories.
For example, the Ponce boys only play in their area and only face teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when that is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for managers, field staff and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
I usually listen to music, watch YouTube clips from my time, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally watch basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
The death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became world-famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a ruthless, fearful, manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night from complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most", the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of her wife in the original series and its sequels, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, his press officer, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate, and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest", Gray said in a statement.
Larry Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking heavily for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made a name for himself on television as a regular character in the NBC series "Jinny of My Dreams" from 1965 to 1970.
In this one, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and took her home.
